[{"id":"FT554750","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"The work on the left is Henry VIII (1540) by Hans Holbein The Younger; the work on the right is Chefren, created about 2500 B.C.E. in Egypt. Discuss the ways in which the artists of these works convey the power and authority of each ruler.&nbsp;","features":[{"type":"sharedpassage","html":"<p>LEFT:</p>\n<img alt=\"A painting of King Henry the Eighth in full regalia. He wears an intricately embroidered doublet, a fur-lined coat with blooming sleeves and a chain across the lapels, and an embroidered hat. He wears a thick, long chain with a circular pendant and rings in his fingers. One of his hands clutches a pair of gloves, while the other hand rests on the hilt of his sword. \n\" height=\"358\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/media.academicmerit.com/6da69c7043cb44c6efbc0e5e3eebc3fe/original.jpg\" width=\"300\" />\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>RIGHT:</p>\n<img alt=\"A photo shows a stone statue of Chefren seated on an engraved throne, viewed from the side. A bird is perched on the throne behind Chefren's head.\" height=\"446\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/media.academicmerit.com/ef646faf65733f3e1baaea704ce41b55/original.png\" width=\"300\" />"}]}]